tool.name: Verify_Depression_Tool

param.name: inFeatClass
param.dialogReference: This is the input Bathymetric Low features.

param.name: outFeatClass
param.dialogReference: This is the output (updated) Bathymetric Low features.

param.name: areaRatioT
param.dialogReference: This is the area ratio threshold between the area of the closed-contour and the area of the input feature. Must be between 0 and 1.

param.name: maxContour
param.dialogReference: This is the maximum number of unique contours that is allowed to generate by the verification process. Must be a positive integer.

tool.summary:
The classification rule for the Depression Feature in the "Classify Bathymetric Low Features Tool" does not apply the "closed-contour" criterion defined in the Dove et al. (2020) morphology scheme. This tool uses the "closed-contour" criterion to verify whether a bathymetric low feature originally classified as Depression is indeed a proper Depression. The verification process evaluates one original Depression Feature at a time. The key steps of the verification process are as follows.

1. Get the polygon area of the original Depression Feature (A0).

2. Buffer the original Depression Feature with a distance equals the cell size of the bathymetry grid.

3. Extract the bathymetry grid to the extent of the buffered feature.

4. Generate contour polygon(s) within the extracted bathymetry grid.

5. Evaluate whether the maximum contour polygon area satisfies the area ratio criterion (the Area Ratio Threshold parameter).

6. The above steps 4 & 5 are iterative process determined by the Maximum Number of Unique Contours parameter.

a. Start with generating contours with 2 or 3 distinct contour values (e.g., 2 or 3 unique contours),

b. If one or more of these contours are closed-contours, convert them to polygons,

c. Clip the contour polygon(s) with the original Depression Feature polygon,

d. Get the polygon area of the largest clipped contour polygons (A1),

e. Calculate the ratio between A1 and A0, and

f. Evaluate if the ratio is greater than the Area Ratio Threshold parameter. If yes, the original Depression Feature is indeed a proper Depression and the verification process is terminated. Otherwise, continue to the next iteration by generating more unique contours then steps from b-f.

7. If after completing all iterations, the area ratio criterion is still not satisfied, the original Depression Feature is reclassified as the "unclassified" class.

Note that the buffering step is needed to allow higher chance of generating closed-contour polygon within a very small (original) Depression Feature. Also note that that the multiprocessing capability is used to speed up the verification processes described above.

searchKeys.keyword: This tool verifies whether a bathymetric low feature originally classified as Depression is indeed a proper Depression according to the closed-contour criterion.
